<div class='article-title'>Fostering Innovation</div>
<div class='article'>
    Abstracted from my "<a href="files/Innovation.pptx" target="_BLANK">Fostering Innovation with the Agile Methodology</a>" presentation.<br /><br />
    <span style='font-size: 1.1em; letter-spacing: 1px'>Everyone wants it.  Everyone needs it.  But few know how to define it, or what it takes to make it.</span><br /><br />
    You can't buy it, but you can borrow it.  You can't inherit it, or get it from a book, a seminar, a class, or an inspirational poster.  You have to grow it from within, but here's the catch:  No matter how much
    desire you may have, "Innovation" may always allude you.
    <br /><br />
    But this isn't just my opinion, as this article from <a href='https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/238545' target='_BLANK'>Entrepreneur.com</a> perfectly states:<br /><br />
    <p class='article-quote'>
        It is important to understand where innovation doesn’t come from:  It doesn’t come from a blog, a book or an article. It doesn’t come from inspirational quotes and stories. It doesn’t come from LinkedIn Influencers or anyone you follow on Twitter. It doesn’t come from motivational speakers. And it most certainly doesn’t come from any kind of self-improvement or personal productivity
        <br /><br />
        Innovation comes from inside you. Ideas, inspiration and innovation only seem to come from outside you, but they don’t. They always come from inside you. The only exception is small teams...but only intimate groups in real time in the real world, never large-scale or online collaborations
    </p>
    The ability to innovate isn't like a recessive trait that can be unlocked by the proper amount of cajoling, or through inspirational words.  Innovation must be fostered, or grown, and you must have the right
    material to work with.  It has been my experience that the first key to unleashing innovation is to create the proper type of work environment, one that is serious about collaboration and mutual respect, rather than just paying lip-service to those qualities, and then fill that environment with the right mix of people with the right characteristics. More on those characteristics later.<br />
    <br />
    There are two basic models of work environments that we find in industries which aspire to be innovative.  The first is the Authoritarian "East-Coast" style of management which values accountability, and the
    second is the egalitarian "West-Coast" model which values flexibility and adaption.  The East-Coast model is referred to as "Frenetic", since you have the appearance of lots of activity, but in truth little progress, while
    the "West-Coast" model is referred to as "Innovative".   Below are some (but certainly not all) of the characteristics of each work environment:<br /><br />

