<br /><br />
To innovate, a certain amount of creativity must be employed, and to be creative people must have the freedom to voice opinions and share ideas, but the East-Coast model tends to see innovation as originating from the
top down, which is unlike the West-Coast model which has a more "flat" hierarchy and which allows ideas to spring from many more places. Ideas drive innovation, and to get the ball rolling, you must have an environment where collaboration and idea sharing are encouraged.<br /><br />

After you have the work environment set up, you then have to fill that work environment with people, but here's where things get sticky:  Not everyone can be innovative, and in fact, many specifically are not interested in
attempting innovation.  We are population of individuals, and though each of us are equal at one level, we are far from equal on other levels.  Some people are naturally innovative.  Some people like the status quo.  The challenge
is to identify who is who, since we don't want to put an individual in a position where they first, don't want to be, and second, will not be as successful.  Think of it in terms of baseball... the person playing catcher
and does a good job would not do a similar good job as a center fielder, and vice versa... the star center fielder would be wasted at catcher as well.  Find the right people for each role, and watch out for favoritism.<br /><br />

So, how do find "the right" people?  First, stop looking for the elusive "<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Purple_squirrel" target="_BLANK">Purple Squirrel</a>".  They aren't out there, and if they are, you probably can't afford them.  Plus there's an added bonus to growing the skill base from within,
since in most cases, your best talent will end up being home-grown.<br /><br />

For me personally, I've found tools like the <a href="http://www.myersbriggs.org/my-mbti-personality-type/mbti-basics/" target="_BLANK">MBTI</a> to be invaluable for identifying those individuals who will excel in roles
where being innovative is required, and those who will excel in other roles not related to constant change.

